=begin
Input: An array (with integer elements n) 
Output: An integer s

Explicit Requirements:
- s represents the minimum number of elements to be changed to
## create an arithmetic progression. 
- The progression must consist of integer elements
- Swapping two elements counts as changing both elements 
-  2 <= arr.length <= 100 
- -1000 <= arr[i] <= 1000 

Implicit Requirements:
- The difference between elements can't be a float so 
steps must be taken to correct for this
-

Examples and edge cases: 
1) [1, 3, 0, 7, 9] 
- difference == 2 
- final array = [1, 3, 5, 7, 9] 
- number of changed elements == 1 

Data structure: 
Use arrays, select and map statements 

High-Level-Algorithm:
- hard: build a progression for each element in the original array using the difference
-- select all values in the progression that are equal to the original
-- map it to size
- select the minimum size

Detailed Algorithm (Pseudo Code): 
- Initialize array to hold all sizes of pseudo progressions
- Initialize an array of arrays to hold all valid differences (arr_arrdiffs)
- Find frequency of difference
- Find all possible progression




=end 

# Test cases 
test_1 = [1, 3, 0, 7, 9] 
test_2 = [1, 10, 2, 12, 3, 14, 4, 16, 5] 

def valid_differences(array)
    # returns an array of arrays
    all_diffs = []
    (0...(array.size-1)).each do |idx|
        difference = [] 
        ((idx + 1)...array.size).each do |ydx|
            next if (array[ydx] - array[idx]) % (ydx - idx) != 0 
            difference.push((array[ydx] - array[idx]) / (ydx - idx))
            all_diffs << difference
        end
    end
    all_diffs
end

def most_frequent_difference(arr_arrs)
    arr_arrs.flatten!.max_by { |difference| arr_arrs.count(difference) }
end 

## This brute force method works, but is very inefficient. 
def all_progressions(arr, progression_val)
    progressions = []
    arr.each_with_index do |value, idx|
        progression = [value] 
        (idx - 1).downto(0) { |_| progression.unshift(-1*progression_val + progression[0] ) } unless idx == 0 
        (idx + 1).upto(arr.size-1) { |_| progression.push(progression_val + progression[-1] ) }
        progressions << progression 
    end
    progressions 
end 

def fix_progression(arr) 
    valid_differences = valid_differences(arr) 
    progression_value = most_frequent_difference(valid_differences)
    all_progressions = all_progressions(arr, progression_value)

    smallest_differences = all_progressions.map do |progression|
        progression.select.each_with_index do |value, idx|
            value != arr[idx] 
        end.size
    end.min 
end 

